Folds II, VI & VII of Barnes (1996)

This source represents the Boby Stream Fault and Mound anticline structure. Steep south dip inferred, aligned to interpretation of the nearby Birch Fault, which is a south dipping reactivated Cretaceous normal fault (Nicol 1993; NZJGG).
NthCant5 of Barnes (1996) & Litchfiled et al (2014)
Pref SR is based on average 4 m vertical uplift of ~18 ka landforms, resolved onto 60 deg fault plane with subordinate dextral obliquity. Min and max are minus and plus 0.15 mm/yr.
Position & Rake edited following CFM workshop. Fault I of Barnes (1996); North Canterbury Shelf 1 of Litchfield et al. (2014)
Position & Rake editied following CFM workshop
Replacement for existing Ashley and Cust fault sources.

Previously Springbank2017 (Goded et al. 2018). Fault tip is buried, with only a broad monoclinal fold at the surface (Jongens et al. 2012). The fault tip is best characterised as being 0.5 km below ground.

Representative source for Springifeld Fault and View Hill Fault (and Kowai Fault). Offsets of basement/Teritary up to ~200 m. SR is about half that of the Hororata source and assumed to be a backthrust (see Dorn et al. 2010).
Representative source for Springifeld Fault and View Hill Fault (and Kowai Fault).  Offsets of basement/Teritary up to ~200 m. In part replaces the SpringfldView source of the CFM
Previously Horoata2017. Rake modified - fold sinuosity at Racecource Hill and Glenroy imply oblique motion
Mw5.9 CHCH EQ aftershock fault rupture
Mw6.0 CHCH EQ aftershock fault rupture
Developed over a Cretaceous normal fault (ChCh QMAP), south dipping downthrown to south
Previously Esk2017. Need to check SR origin with David Barrell because is about half of site SR data.
Redefinition of part of the Waitohi2017 source. This source represents the Hurunui Peak fault zone, with estimated ~8 m high scarp on inferred 18 ka landforms.

Redefinition of part of the Waitohi2017 source. This source represents a dextral transfer structure between the S end of the W-dipping Hurunui Peak fault source, and N end of the SE-dipping Pancake fault source.

Accommodates a redefinition of part of the Esk2017 source. This source represents the SE dipping strucutre on SE side of upper Waitohi valley. Pref SR is based on nominal  5 m vertical uplift of ~18 ka landforms.
Represents a mapped fault in bedrock, of the same name. Orientation and profoundly deformed late Cenozoic strata provide basis of inclusion. Birdseye fault scarp height of inferred 18 ka age.
See UC theses by Mittelstadt and Noble c. 2011 for data. SR 3.4 m reverse dip slip on 21-23.3 ka surface
Would recommend similar parameters to Esk when complied. Esk Fault cf Mittelstaedt (2011) SR 3.4 m reverse dip slip on 21-23.3 ka surface
Previously Shingly. Harper Fault Zone long standing named fault
Pref SR is based on average 8 m vertical uplift of ~18 ka landforms, resolved onto 60 deg fault plane with subordinate dextral obliquity. Min and max are minus and plus 0.15 mm/yr
SR and sense changed in accordanc with Santosh Dhakal s upcoming PhD submission

Reinterpreted as predominantly SS fault; with dextral reverse dipping south based on Howard et al 2005 trench data. Pref SR based on 7 m horiz offset from Howard et al. 2005, with updated age of land surface of 17 ka from Putnam et al. 2013.

Prominent fault block, up to 0.5 km throw on peneplain; correlated with Quaternary faults at Rakiaia Gorge. Best SR based on ~30 m throw on ~165 ka lake sediments, resolved onto 60 deg pure reverse fault (sense inferred from strike).

Suspected but not confirmed post-glacial scarps; SR pref based on 2.5 m scarp on ~18 ka surface, max is value given by Barrell 2009, and min a bit smaller than pref. Assumed pure reverse, dips from CFM retained.

Suspected but not confirmed post-glacial scarps; SR pref based on 2.5 m scarp on ~18 ka surface, max is value given by Barrell 2009. Assumed pure reverse, dips from CFM retained. Revised version of part of Double Hill Fault of CFM
Becomes non-seismogenic based on the reasoning of McVerry et al. 2017 (CR2017/160)
Dips from Litchfield et al. Revised SRs based on outwash plain offset west of Mt John, with 10 m scarp height from lidar, and well-dated outwash plain.
Basement rock with well-defined peneplain surface uplifted ~200 m to the west against peneplain remnants.  No known Quat offsets, nominal slip rate applied.

Basement rock uplifted hundreds of metres to the west against Tertiary outlier and extrensive peneplain dip slope. New name to avoid confusion with active Blue Mountain Fault in South Otago. No known Quat offsets, nominal slip rate applied.

Structure contours of Barrell and Strong (2012 - CR2012/245) point to a substantial SE-striking fault, with localised likely recent scarps (Barrell and Strong 2010 - CR2010/147). Extrapolated SE based on QMAP faults

SR and dips from Litchfield et al. 2013. QC value of 2 reflects that despite limited direct investigation, excellent preservation of age-contrained fluvial surfaces across the fault provides evidence for recent tectonics.

Brothers rangefront is not conducive to scarp preservation, and Litchfield et al. SR revised to accord with that for Maungati Fault, which underlies terraced areas more suitable for preserving deformation.

Prominent fault block, basement exposed in centre, hundreds of metres of Late Cenozoic uplift. No known Quat offsets, but mid-late Q uplift can be inferred NE of Geraldine. Slow SR, slightly above nominal, inferred.
Adjusted linework to accord with the structure contouring interpretations of Barrell and Strong 2012 (CR2012/245) . Rake revised to include dextral component. SRs from Litchfield et al.

Assumed 10 m deformation of landforms of inferred age range 70-200 ka, 140 ka best estimate. SR range from age end-members applied to dip end-members. QC = 4 reflects existence of some contraints on the regional landform sequence ages
Adjusted linework to accord with the structure contouring interpretations of Barrell and Strong 2012 (CR2012/245) . Rake revised to include dextral component. SRs from Litchfield et al.

Following the discussion of Barrell 2016, the  Longden  Holocene fault scarp is interpreted to contain the southern end of the Dalgety source, the Dalgety Fault also having some relatively young fault scarps on hillslopes. SR from Litchfield et al.

Formerly identified as part of Opawa Fault (Litchfield et al. 2013).  SR from Litchfield et al., lack of known deformation on relatively old fans and terraces is basis for slow SRs and QC of 4 in 100 ky timeframe

Major ~N-striking fault in bedrock, that has uplifted the Grampian Mountains that separate Hakatarmea valley from Mackenzie basin, with peneplain offset of as much as ~1000 m. No evidence for LQ offset, nominal slip rates assigned.
Name reverts to the long-standing term on geological maps and literature for this structure,  Hunters Fault . SR from Litchfield et al. 2014, rake revised to entertain small dextral component.

SR and dips from Litchfield et al. 2013. QC value of 2 reflects that despite limited direct investigation, excellent preservation of age-contrained fluvial surfaces across the fault provides evidence for recent tectonics.

Major fault in bedrock, with the Benmore Range showing as much as ~1200 m uplift of the peneplain to the southwest. Nominal slip rates inferred. Similarity of strike to Waitangi Fault forms basis for inferring possible dextral component

Major ~N-striking fault in bedrock, with uplift of unnamed range (highest point, Mt Sutton) northeast of the Aviemore basin.  There is no recognised Late Quaternary deformation, although rugged hill terrain reduces likelihood of its preservation.

Previously Lindis Pass. ~5 m high scarp on inferred Holocene-age landforms pref SR 0.5 mm/yr, min SR of 0.1 mm/yr reflecting scarp could be single rupture,  max SR of 2x the pref, acknowledging uncertainties in scarp height and/or landform age inference
Major fault in bedrock, with uplift of unnamed range north of the Aviemore basin, with offset of the peneplain of typically as much as ~500 m. There is no recognised Late Quaternary deformation.

Recognition of LQ deformation and structural interpretation discussed in detail by Barrell (2016). Structural continuity with Brothers Fault is basis for assigning it the same SR as the Maungati Fault.
Following the reasoning of Barrell 2016, the Kirkliston source is repositioned to the east side of the Mt MacGregor ridge, and now closely abut the south end of the Dalgety source

SR and dips from Litchfield et al. 2013. Minor revision to linework. QC value of 3 reflects that investigation has only been undertaken on a limited sector of the fault source, which includes a series of seperately named fault entities
Peneplain offset of typically ~500 m. There is no recognised Late Quaternary deformation, although rugged hill terrain reduces likelihood of its preservation. Nominal slip rates inferred.

SR and dips from Litchfield et al. 2013. Note that this is a partially reactivated normal fault, hence the prominent topographic expression (higher to NE) is on the Late Quaternary kinematically downthrown side.

Major fault in bedrock, up to 1 km Late Cenozoic peneplain offset. Blue Lake SR is applied to the Hawkdun Fault. No recognised Quaternary scarps, though in the mountain-front setting, conceivable no long-term recognisable surface evidence persists

Barrell et al. 2005 show evidence for no movement since at least 62 ka; low nominal slip rate (as for other  no known activity  faults) assigned. Position of trace relocated to the SW to accord bett+AC137+AC85
This was formerly the Otematata fault source. Doubtful evidence for Late Quaternary movement; nominal slip rates applied

Inferred fault in bedrock, peneplain offset of several hundred metres. Definite fault scarp at N end of fault, and likely ones at far south end of fault. Barrell 2019 proposes 0.2 mm/yr SR, adopted here as pref. Nominal SR min/max

Major fault in bedrock, up to 1 km Late Cenozoic peneplain offset.  Barrell 2019 uses post-Miocene throw on peneplan to obtain SR of 0.07 mm/yr. This is porposes as pref. SR, with nominal min and max of 0.02 and 0.15 respectively.

SR from Litchfield et al. 2013; based on Barrell et al. (2002, 2009). Possible association with the SW-dipping Wharekuri Fault. QC of 3 reflects that investigation has only been undertaken at one location at the northern end of the fault source.

Up up to 1 km Late Cenozoic throw.  Hunters Fault dips and rakes applied. Nominal slow SRs aplied. Lack of known deformation on relatively old fans and terraces is basis for slow SRs and QC of 4 in 100 ky timeframe

Array of east-facing Quaternary fault scarps/monoclines, inferred association W-dipping bedrock fault. Interpred as a back-fault off Omaranma Saddle Fault; Barrell 2019 assigned SR as not independently rupturing structure.
Max and min slip rates from younger and older bounds of most recent rupture documented by Barrell et al. 2005, with best rate being between those two values

Major fault in bedrock, with as much as ~500 m offset of the peneplain, up to the southeast. Proposed as possible active fault by Barrell 2016. No definitive evidence for Late Quaternary movement, and nominal slip rates inferred.
Major fault in bedrock, with as much as ~1200 m uplift of the peneplain to the southwest. There is no recognised Late Quaternary deformation, nominal slip rates inferred.

Major fault in bedrock, up to 1 km reverse-fault movement to create Late Cenozoic peneplain offset. Barrell 2019 interprets a scarp on the Stranraer Fault near Naseby as related to Waihemo FZ rupture, and derives a 0.12 mm/yr SR pref

Marine terrace height change (~7 m) is the main evidence for activity. Due to N-S strike, it is assessed as pure dip slip, and assigned a preferred slip rate of 0.1 mm/yr (9 m vertical offset since ~125 ka, resolved onto a 45 degree fault plane.

Sourced from the Cox et al. 2012 interpretation, the fault as delineated in the NZAFM stepped across several fault structures, some identified as normal faults. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).
Ahuriri  fault zone revision to  Hopkins Fault . Estimated scarp heights (5 to 10 m) on an inferred 18 ka land surface inform the slip rate estimates,

Sourced from the Cox et al. 2012. Dobson revised to Barrier Range cf QMAP. Position refined to accord better with geological mapped location. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).
Indicated fault(s) in bedrock; named  Makarora Fault in NZAFM; for precedence, name reverts to Wanaka Fault (Turnbull 2000). Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps)

Indicated fault(s) in bedrock; Hunter Fault to Hunter Valley Fault (Turnbull 2000). Indicated post-glacial fault scarp. The min SR acknowledges single post-glacial rupture could account for the surface scarp, therefore SR unconstrained maximum

Dingle Burn  in NZAFM, name  Dingle Fault  as used in QMAP datasets is applied here. General summit elevations either side of the line of the fault indicate NW-dipping reverse fault. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).
Refer to detailed description and dicussion in Barrell 2019a, regarding revised mapping of the north and south sectors of the Moonlight Fault, downgrading of its activity and slip rates

Major fault in bedrock, indicated post-glacial offset;  Livingstone Fault  used in preference to  Livingstone Key Summit FZ . Barrell 2019 SR of 1.0 mm/yr,reduced 50% as fault is not prominent across glacial landforms in upper Eglinton valley.

Major fault in bedrock; post-glacial scarps near Lake Wakatipu previously attributed to Moonlight Fault attributed to West Wakatipu Fault by Barrell 2019. Min and max SR vary by 50% from the preferred value

Interpretation follows Barrell 2019. Estimated scarp heights of ~5 m on an inferred 18 ka land surface inform SR. The max SR allows that that scarp height, or landform age, could be up to 50% in error.
Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset; nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps)
pref SR of 0.1 mm/yr retained, as no surface rupture since ~30 ka but 80 m deformation of lake silts, of age estimate in range of ~150 ka to ~450 ka, 330 ka preferred (Barrell 2019).
Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset; nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps)

Formerly SE Cardrona Fault (Beanland and Barrow-Hurlbert 1988), the new name avoids possible confusion with the  NW Cardona Fault  (Barrell 2019). Major fault in bedrock, peneplain offset; nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).

Faults in bedrock offsetting peneplain, and assessed monoclinal deformation of  post-Lindis -age lake silt. Formerly part of the  Pisa  fault source, (e.g. Bealand and Berryman 1989) as the  Lindis Peak  segment of the Pisa Fault,

SW end lengthened slightly to approach the Old Man Fault. The Fish Creek and Cairnmuir faults are interpreted as abandoned strands of the Dunstan fault zone, and not regarded as independent fault sources

End-points revised, shortened to north (see Cluden Fault Zone) and lengthened to south to include Carrick and Bannockburn fault strands; Pisa fault source positioned midway between those strands. NZAFM slip rates retained.
Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset. Proposed rename Raggedy to Raggedy-Blackstone, as used in the Barrrell 2019 which highlights geological name plus the seismic source name used subsequently.

Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset of several hundred metres. NZAFM included in Gimmerburn, independent source is suggested here, given the fault s length, sizeable offset. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).

Complex stepping fault zone; of the order of ~400 m offset of peneplain. Surface exposure dating implies ~60 m uplift since ~500 ka; uplift rate on 45 deg fault gives min SR of ~0.1 mm/yr. Preferred SR based on ~5 m scarp on estimate 18 ka fan
Fault in bedrock, extrapolated south into Maniototo basin along topographic anomaly; also indicated in geophysics (Glass Earth). Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).

Comprises NNE-striking Launceston Fault, up to the W, and Ranfurly Fault Zone, a complex and wide array of ENE-striking fault scarps. Via inference Barrell 2019 assigned a 0.1 mm/yr SR, noting that scarp freshness implies Holocene rupture

Array of faults in bedrock, and monoclines in Cenzoic strata. Comprises NE Waipiata. Re-interpretations described by Barrell 2019. An inferred back-fault is interpreted to have deformed fluvial terraces of the Kye Burn valley. SR are nominal inferences.

Reconsideration of trench data interpretations by  Griffin (unpublished data) indicates ~6 m  net slip since ~23 ka, suggesting 0.25 mm/y best estimate. Max is 20% more, and min allows that the slip amount may be all that has occurred since ~65 ka.

Array of faults in bedrock, peneplain offsets. Fault source near NW side of fault array (Blackmans Fault- Galloway Fault). Possible scarp on alluvial fan defines pref SR. Min SR recognises scarp may not be tectonic, max recognises difficult preservation

Array of faults in bedrock, peneplain offsets; typical peneplain throw across the array is ~300 m. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps). Source line positioned broadly along the middle of the array
Inferred fault in bedrock; peneplain offset. Interpreted as a back-fault splay off the Galloway Fault Zone, and not an independent fault source

Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset ~150-200 m. Called Taieri Ridge Fault (Stirling et al 2012; Litchfield et al. 2013, Horse Flat Fault has precedence in literature (Barrell 2016, 2021). Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).

Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset (up to ~300 m throw). Late Quaternary scarps collectively as much as ~8 m high on alluvial fans of inferred age. Barrell 2019a estimated 0.18 m pref SR, min SR nominal 0.05 mm/yr, max SR is 2x preferred

Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset typically ~50-100 m but locally as much as 250 m (Barrell 2016). Includes Macraes Fault along strike to the northeast. No evidence for Late Quaternary movement, and nominal slip rates inferred.
Inferred en-echelon faults in bedrock, peneplain offset ~50 m up to the SE. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).

Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset as much as ~100 m (Barrell 2020). Identified as possible fault source by Villamor et al. 2018. No evidence for Late Quaternary movement, and nominal slip rates inferred.
Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset  typically ~50-100 m but locally as much as 150 m (Barrell 2020). No evidence for Late Quaternary movement, and nominal slip rates inferred.
Inferred fault in bedrock, peneplain offset, ~100 m up to the west. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).
Fault(s) in bedrock, peneplain offset  typically ~50-100 m but locally as much as 200 m (Barrell 2020). No recognised evidence for Late Quaternary movement, and nominal slip rates inferred.

Inferred fault in bedrock, peneplain offset, as much as ~350 m up to the southeast. Comprises SW Waipiata. Re-interpretations described by Barrell 2019. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).
Inferred fault in bedrock, peneplain offset, as much as ~200 m up to the east. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).
Barrell 2019 lengthened the west end, as per above; overall length increased ~6 km

Hyde_south corresponds to  The Twins moncline  described by Barrell 2020. Best slip rate is 50% of the Hyde north rate, as discussed by Barrell 2020. Classified N-PS due to lack of direct evidence for LQ surface deformation
Inferred fault in bedrock, peneplain offset, as much as ~200 m up to the west. Nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).

Inferred monocline in bedrock, based on indicated deformation of peneplain . Along strike of termination of Flat Stream Fault. No evidence for or against Late Quaternary deformation. Nominal slip rates inferred.
Currently drawn as three segments, as per Barrell et al. (2020).

Barrell 2020 used term Waipori-Maungatua-North Taieri Fault to more clearly reflect its geologically-mapped component structures, but simplified Maungatua-North Taieri Fault retained as a fault source name (as used by Villamor et al. 2018).
Barrell 2020 suggestion that it is a splay off the Titri and not an independent fault source. For the moment, it is assigned the nominal SR (0.05 pref) applied to other faults of doubtful activity
NE limit shortened to allow extension of Waipori Fault; SW end lengthened, about the same net length

Barrell 2020 suggested that recency of trace on GIF suggests association with Holocene Akatore rupture (triggered?). Holocene net amount (4.8 to 7.4 m - median 6.1 m) from Taylor-Silva et al. 2020 applied over 5 ka timeframe.
Shortened to allow extension of Waipori Fault; Barrell 2019 proposes as a splay of the No. 1 fault, not an independent source
Currently drawn as three segments, as per Barrell et al. (2020).

Barrell 2020 suggested that recency of trace on Green Island Fault suggests association with Holocene Akatore rupture (triggered?). Holocene net amount (4.8 to 7.4 m - median 6.1 m) from Taylor-Silva et al. 2020 applied over 5 ka timeframe.
Currently drawn as three segments, as per Barrell et al. (2020).

A N-S array of fault scarps in the  Cardrona  range, called the Highland Fault, is interpreted as a splay of the Motatapu Fault (Barrell 2019). Preferred SR is from surface scarps of assumed post-glacial age.

Formerly northwest end NW Cardrona Fault. Fault in bedrock, but no recognisable post-glacial surface deformation. Nominal preferred SR of 0.05 mm/yr, min SR of 0.025 acknowledges proximity to Quaternery-active faults

2-segment model of NSHM retained, but fault lengths and end-positions altered. Recalculated age data from Bealand and Barrow Hurlbert (1988) indicate a max SR of 0.2 at Kawarau valley, and post-glacial monocline deformation at Wanaka implies ~0.3 mm/yr

2-segment model of NSHM retained, but fault lengths and end-positions altered. Recalculated age data from Bealand and Barrow Hurlbert (1988) indicate a max SR of 0.2 at Kawarau valley, and post-glacial monocline deformation at Wanaka implies ~0.3 mm/yr

Equates in part ot  Gentle Annie Fault  of Beanland and Barrow-Hurlbert 1988, as explained by Barrell 2019. Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset; nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps).

The max SR only slightly more than preferred SR (0.4; from NSHM/NZAFM) indicates that preferred SR is likely to be close to a maximum. Barrell 2019 raises possibility of segmented rupture based on small single event displacements.

Refer to detailed description and discussion in Barrell 2019a, regarding revised mapping of the north and south sectors of the Moonlight Fault, downgrading of its activity and slip rates. Southern limit placed at north end of Takitimu Mountains
Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset; nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps)
Slip rates revised from NSHM/NZAFM; preferred SR uses adopted age of  Lindis Gravel , max and min assume age differs by 50% from that estimate
Fault in bedrock, peneplain offset; nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps)

Represents an en-cechelon array of fault slices, that uplift basement to the E against Tertiary strata by many hundreds of metres. No reported evidence for Late Q deformation, nominal slip rates applied.

Connects Late Q scarps on Five Rivers Plain and fault scarp up Acton Stream, shown on QMAP. Approx 2 m scarp on ~18 ka surface basis for slip rates, plus topographic expression (up to E) in hill country.
Inferred to account for prominent elevation of the Mid Dome ridge, up to ~1 km throw on peneplain.  Nominal slip rates, mod-steep east dip, and some movement obliquity inferred.
Fault in bedrock, indicated peneplain offset; slip rates adopted from adjacent Old Man Fault

This source is sub-parallel to the Waikaia source. Name is from QMAP, throw has uplifted the Black Umbrella Range, by hundreds of metres relative to Tertiary outliers. No reported evidence for Late Q deformation, nominal slip rates applied.

Referred to by Cater and Norris as  Takitimu Boundary Fault Zone ; complex fault zone. Remanent Quat scarps. Accounts for main uplift of Takitimu Mountains. Fault dips and rake is guess. Scarps on old fans give slip rate estimates (see Barrell 2019)
Minor change in location of northern tip - attributes modified to those of Hillfoot for continuity of structure - evidence for LQ activity equivical
Realigned with mapped QMAP Monowai Fault - dip direction changed re QMAP

Preferred slip rate reinterpreted from data in Pace et al. 2005; min and max are half and twice respectively. SW end of fault source shortened by ~17 km, as that sector was on a different fault, with an opposing sense of throw (down to the SE)
Reversed Cretaceous normal fault. Probable offset Clutha River terraces give preferred SR; SR min and max are half and twice respectively; revised from Villamor et al. 2018
Uplifts Murihiku basement against Tertiary inlier, and acconts for uplift of Taringatura Hills (several hundred metres of relief). QMAP shows locally preseved Late Q scarp.
Preferred slip rate from data in Pace et al. 2005; min and max are half and twice respectively
Fault in bedrock, indicated peneplain offset; nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps)

Uplifts the Hokonui Hills and represents that strucural margin fault zone that controls the famed Gore structural gap across the Southland Syncline in basement rock. No reported Late Q activity, nominal slip rates applied.
Fault in bedrock, indicated peneplain offset; nominal slip rates (no known Late Quaternary scarps)
Fault location changed to coincide with previously mapped fault
Indicated offset hillsides; rates inferred from Otanomomo Fault, with which it is suggested to rupture
Fault in bedrock, indicated peneplain offset; likely to rupture with or instead of Hillfoot Fault (i.e not independent source); nominal slip rates inferred (no known Late Quaternary scarps)
Indicated offset Clutha river terraces; suggested to rupture together with Clifton Fault
Northern tip moved for consistency with Solander-1
Faster short-term Holocene slip estimate, slower last interglacial slip estimate
Northern tip aligned with Hauroko North as major throughgoing feature
Extended north - geomorphology indicates continuity of structure
Previously Litchfield et al (2014) SW6-10 + SW3
